Diagnostic remarks.
A large, long-legged, and strongly sexually dimorphic katydid. Males have long and wide tegmina with a characteristic venation; they are good fliers (
Fig. 32C
). Females have narrow tegmina that do not reach the hind knees and are incapable of flight (
Fig. 32D
). The tympana on the front tibia are articulate (enclosed in cuticular folds) on both sides, the male cerci are simple, with a small, apical inner spine (
Fig. 32B
), and the ovipositor is long, curved, and with distinct serration at the apical portions of both valvulae (
Fig. 32A
).
